1360","1344":"1344","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1330":"1330","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1371":"1371","1360":"1360","about 1375":"about 1375","Tiverton,Bunbury,Cheshire,England.":"Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Tiverton, Bunbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Moston (Lancs), Moston by Chester or Moston Green (both Cheshire), or Moston in Stanton upon Hine Heath (Shrops). There has probably been some confusion with (2).","2  Welsh, English:  see  Mostyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mosson","meanings":["1  English: in Gloucs perhaps a variant of   Mawson  . Compare Tacie Mawson, 1570 in   IGI   (Elmore, Gloucs); John Mawson, 1645 in   IGI   (Kings Stanley, Gloucs). Otherwise see (2).","2  English: variant of   Moston   with assimilation of the /t/ to the preceding /s/. Compare Jois. Mosson, 1620, Thomæ Moston, 1630 in   IGI   (Astbury, Cheshire); John Moston, 1637, John Mosson, 1673 in   IGI   (Prees, Shrops); William Mosson, 1669, William Moston, 1715 in   IGI   (Saint Giles Cripplegate, London).","3  English:  see  Mossom  ."]},{"name":"Mostin","meanings":["1  English, Welsh:  see  Mostyn  .","2  English:  see  Moston  ."]},{"name":"Mostyn","meanings":["Welsh and English: habitational name from Mostyn in Flintshire, Wales, the name of which is derived from Old English <i>mos</i> ‘bog’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farm, village’.","History: This surname was adopted by a 16th-century Lord of Mostyn, Thomas ap Richard ap Hywel, and his brother Piers."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Moston was born in 1350, in Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William de Moston, was 21 and her mother, Margerite de Brereton, was 20. She married William Hulgreve. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1395, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1350–1395":"1350–1395","1344–1375":"1344–1375","1371–1420":"1371–1420","1330–1360":"1330–1360","1330–1373":"1330–1373","about 1360":"umbes 1360","1344":"1344","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1330":"1330","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1371":"1371","1360":"1360","about 1375":"umbes 1375","Tiverton,Bunbury,Cheshire,England.":"Tiverton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tiverton, Bunbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tiverton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tiverton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1350–1395":"1350–1395","1344–1375":"1344–1375","1371–1420":"1371–1420","1330–1360":"1330–1360","1330–1373":"1330–1373","about 1360":"noin 1360","1344":"1344","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1330":"1330","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1371":"1371","1360":"1360","about 1375":"noin 1375","Tiverton,Bunbury,Cheshire,England.":"Tiverton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Tiverton, Bunbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tiverton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tiverton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1350–1395":"1350–1395","1344–1375":"1344–1375","1371–1420":"1371–1420","1330–1360":"1330–1360","1330–1373":"1330–1373","about 1360":"environ 1360","1344":"1344","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1330":"1330","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1371":